# Design Decisions — 2026-04-13
## Session: Dairy category — structural design before insertion

---

### Decision 1: Lookup layer separation of concerns (confirmed, hard constraint)

The lookup layer does ONE thing: receives an ingredient vector (source, form) and returns
the display name in the required language. That is all. It does not hold categories,
taxonomies, variety-of hierarchies, or any structural information about how ingredients
relate to each other. All of that lives in TypeDB. This is not a soft preference — it is
a separation of concerns that must not be blurred. Any structural relationship between
ingredients belongs in the graph.

---

### Decision 2: Cheese is declarable bare — unlike milk

FSSAI allows "cheese" as a valid ingredient declaration. Declaring "mozzarella" instead
is a voluntary specificity upgrade, not a correction of an underdeclaration. This is
fundamentally different from milk, where specifying cow vs buffalo is REQUIRED because
the source difference has tax, dietary classification, and allergen implications at the
source level itself.

This means:
- `cheese` gets an `ingredient-form` node in IFID (it is declarable)
- `mozzarella`, `cheddar`, `paneer`, `cottage-cheese` also get `ingredient-form` nodes
- The relationship between them is: mozzarella is a recognized sub-type of cheese, both
  independently declarable, specificity is the brand's choice

---

### Decision 3: Form-level variety-of — pattern identified, schema change required

The cheese → mozzarella/cheddar/paneer relationship is structurally isomorphic to
mango → Alphonso mango at the source level:
- Both are declarable at both levels
- More specific = voluntary upgrade, not a required correction
- The specific type IS the general type (mozzarella IS a cheese, Alphonso IS a mango)

`variety-of` currently only connects `source → source` in the schema. It needs to be
extended to also connect `ingredient-form → ingredient-form` for this pattern.

OPEN: Does this pattern appear outside dairy? (spices, fermentation products, marine?)
Must be tested before finalizing. Do not implement in isolation for dairy only.

---

### Decision 4: Sugars are NOT isomorphic to cheese subtypes — do not create form variety-of

Brown sugar vs white sugar is a processual distinction (degree of molasses retention).
The form is crystalline sucrose in both cases. The difference belongs on `processing-method`
on the `form-of` relation — same logic as whole wheat flour vs refined wheat flour sharing
a single `flour` form-id. You can refine brown sugar into white sugar. The distinction
is a processing path, not a categorical identity.

Mozzarella and cheddar cannot be converted into each other. They are legally defined,
categorically distinct product types. This is why cheese subtypes are form-level variety-of
while sugar variants are processing-method on form-of.

---

### Decision 5: Lecithin, vegetable oil specificity is SOURCE-level, not form-level

Sunflower lecithin vs soy lecithin = same form (lecithin), different sources. This is
handled by two form-of paths pointing to the same `lecithin` ingredient-form node from
different source nodes (sunflower, soy). No form-level variety-of needed or appropriate.

"Vegetable oil" does not get an IFID node — it is underdeclared by IFID's standard.
Palm oil, sunflower oil, etc. each derive from their own source nodes.

---

### Decision 6: WPC and WPI are separate form-id nodes

Whey protein concentrate and whey protein isolate are distinctly declared, have different
regulatory status, different protein content thresholds, different functional properties.
They are closer to semolina vs flour (different forms from the same source) than to
whole vs refined wheat flour (same form, different processing path).

Both get separate form-id nodes. The processing-method on form-of from whey captures
HOW they were produced (ultrafiltration-concentration vs ion-exchange-isolation).
The form-id captures WHAT they are (declared identity).

---

### Decision 7: Multi-hop derivation chains already work in current schema

`ingredient-form` already plays `form-of:origin` in the current schema. This means:

    cow milk (source) ← form-of ← whey (ingredient-form) ← form-of ← WPC (ingredient-form)

is structurally valid today without any schema change. Chains of derivation across
declared forms are handled. "All things ultimately derived from cow milk" = multi-hop
traversal.

---

### Open questions not yet resolved

1. Is "whey" declared bare on Indian product labels, or only as "whey powder", "WPC",
   "WPI" etc.? If never bare-declared, whey may not need its own form-id node — WPC/WPI
   could go directly form-of source. Needs verification before inserting.

2. Does form-level variety-of appear in other categories? Must test against spices,
   marine-derived, fermentation products before finalizing the schema extension.
